{"title_page": "Norman Pace", "text_new": "{{for|the American biochemist|Norman R. Pace}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2014}}\n{{Use British English|date=February 2014}}\n{{BLP sources|date=January 2013}}\n\n{{Infobox comedian\n| name = Norman Pace\n| image = \n| caption  = \n| birth_name  = \n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|1953|2|17|df=y}}\n| birth_place  = [[Dudley]], [[West Midlands (region)|West Midlands]]<!--West Midlands pre-1974-->, England\n| active  = \n| genre = \n| influences  = \n| influenced  =  \n| website  =\n}}\n\n'''Norman Pace''' (born 17 February 1953 in [[Dudley]], [[Worcestershire]]<!--Worcestershire pre-1974-->) is an [[England|English]] [[actor]] and [[comedian]], best known as one half of the comedy duo [[Hale and Pace]] with his friend and comic partner [[Gareth Hale]]. Both former teachers, they fronted several television programmes jointly, most notably ''Hale and Pace'', ''Pushing Up Daisies'', ''h&p@bbc'' and ''Jobs for the Boys''.\n\n==Early life==\nHe grew up in [[Newark-on-Trent]] in [[Nottinghamshire]]. He attended the [[Magnus Church of England School|Magnus Grammar School]]. He then went to Avery Hill College, now the [[Avery Hill]] Campus<ref>{{cite web|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100226003827/http://www.gre.ac.uk/about/avery-hill/about/|url=http://www.gre.ac.uk/about/avery-hill/about/|website=University of Greenwich|title=About the Avery Hill Campus|archivedate=26 February 2010}}</ref> of the [[University of Greenwich]], in [[Eltham]] where he gained a [[Bachelor of Education|BEd]] in 1975.\n\n==Work with Gareth Hale==\nAs straight actors they also fronted the original TV dramatisation of ''[[Dalziel and Pascoe]]'', and in 1989 they guest-starred together in the ''[[Doctor Who]]'' serial ''[[Survival (Doctor Who)|Survival]]''. Also in 1989, Hale and Pace won the [[Rose d'Or|Golden Rose of Montreux]]. In 2007 they appeared in the [[List of Extras episodes#Christmas special (2007)|Christmas special of ''Extras'']], called ''The Extra Special Series Finale,'' playing themselves. In 2018 he was acting in the comedy TV series ''[[Benidorm (TV series)|Benidorm]]'' with [[Gareth Hale]]\n\n==Later work==\nNorman Pace later took a direction towards [[theatre]] and starred in ''Chicago'' (Adelphi), ''Breakfast with [[Jonny Wilkinson]]'' and ''[[Our Man in Havana]]'' at the [[Nottingham Playhouse]]. In summer 2010 he appeared as the detective in a touring production of Peter Gordon comedy ''Murdered to Death''. In autumn 2013 he appeared as \"The Showman\" in Michael Eaton's ''[[Charlie Peace: His Amazing Life & Astounding Legend]]'' at the [[Nottingham Playhouse]]. In 2014 Pace was touring in a production of ''[[One Man, Two Guvnors]]''.<ref>{{cite web|website=One Man, Two Guvnors|url=http://www.onemantwoguvnors.com/about-the-show/|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141229230748/http://onemantwoguvnors.com/about-the-show/|title=About The Show|archivedate=29 December 2014}}</ref> He was also a regular presenter for ''The Open'' on the [[Sky Poker]] channel.\n\nIn 2016 he toured with ''[[The Rocky Horror Show]]''<ref>{{cite news|url=http://stv.tv/news/features/1347822-five-minute-interview-norman-pace-on-the-two-rons-and-rocky-horror-show/|title=Five-minute interview: Norman Pace on the Two Rons and Rocky Horror Show|website=STV News|author=Pamela Tulloch|date=28 March 2016}}</ref> and in 2017 the new production of ''[[Hairspray (musical)|Hairspray]]'', playing the role of Wilbur Turnblad.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wintergardensblackpool.co.uk/uncategorized/hairspray-the-musical-star-cast-announcement/|title=Hairspray the Musical Star Cast Announcement|website=Winter Gardens Blackpool|date=5 June 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170809191349/http://www.wintergardensblackpool.co.uk/uncategorized/hairspray-the-musical-star-cast-announcement/|archivedate=9 August 2017}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|name=Norman Pace|id=0655154}}\n* [http://pokerdb.thehendonmob.com/player.php?a=r&n=28024 Norman Pace Hendon Mob poker tournament results]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pace, Norman}}\n[[Category:1953 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Greenwich]]\n[[Category:English male comedians]]\n[[Category:English male television actors]]\n[[Category:Poker commentators]]\n[[Category:People from Newark-on-Trent]]\n[[Category:People educated at Magnus Church of England School]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Nottinghamshire]]\n[[Category:People from Dudley]]\n[[Category:Male actors from the West Midlands (county)]]\n[[Category:English male stage actors]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|the American biochemist|Norman R. Pace}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2014}}\n{{Use British English|date=February 2014}}\n{{BLP sources|date=January 2013}}\n\n{{Infobox comedian\n| name = Norman Pace\n| image = \n| caption  = \n| birth_name  = \n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|1953|2|17|df=y}}\n| birth_place  = [[Dudley]], [[West Midlands]]<!--West Midlands pre-1974-->, England\n| active  = \n| genre = \n| influences  = \n| influenced  =  \n| website  =\n}}\n\n'''Norman Pace''' (born 17 February 1953 in [[Dudley]], [[Worcestershire]]<!--Worcestershire pre-1974-->) is an [[England|English]] [[actor]] and [[comedian]], best known as one half of the comedy duo [[Hale and Pace]] with his friend and comic partner [[Gareth Hale]]. Both former teachers, they fronted several television programmes jointly, most notably ''Hale and Pace'', ''Pushing Up Daisies'', ''h&p@bbc'' and ''Jobs for the Boys''.\n\n==Early life==\nHe grew up in [[Newark-on-Trent]] in [[Nottinghamshire]]. He attended the [[Magnus Church of England School|Magnus Grammar School]]. He then went to Avery Hill College, now the [[Avery Hill]] Campus<ref>{{cite web|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100226003827/http://www.gre.ac.uk/about/avery-hill/about/|url=http://www.gre.ac.uk/about/avery-hill/about/|website=University of Greenwich|title=About the Avery Hill Campus|archivedate=26 February 2010}}</ref> of the [[University of Greenwich]], in [[Eltham]] where he gained a [[Bachelor of Education|BEd]] in 1975.\n\n==Work with Gareth Hale==\nAs straight actors they also fronted the original TV dramatisation of ''[[Dalziel and Pascoe]]'', and in 1989 they guest-starred together in the ''[[Doctor Who]]'' serial ''[[Survival (Doctor Who)|Survival]]''. Also in 1989, Hale and Pace won the [[Rose d'Or|Golden Rose of Montreux]]. In 2007 they appeared in the [[List of Extras episodes#Christmas special (2007)|Christmas special of ''Extras'']], called ''The Extra Special Series Finale,'' playing themselves. In 2018 he was acting in the comedy TV series ''[[Benidorm (TV series)|Benidorm]]'' with [[Gareth Hale]]\n\n==Later work==\nNorman Pace later took a direction towards [[theatre]] and starred in ''Chicago'' (Adelphi), ''Breakfast with [[Jonny Wilkinson]]'' and ''[[Our Man in Havana]]'' at the [[Nottingham Playhouse]]. In summer 2010 he appeared as the detective in a touring production of Peter Gordon comedy ''Murdered to Death''. In autumn 2013 he appeared as \"The Showman\" in Michael Eaton's ''[[Charlie Peace: His Amazing Life & Astounding Legend]]'' at the [[Nottingham Playhouse]]. In 2014 Pace was touring in a production of ''[[One Man, Two Guvnors]]''.<ref>{{cite web|website=One Man, Two Guvnors|url=http://www.onemantwoguvnors.com/about-the-show/|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141229230748/http://onemantwoguvnors.com/about-the-show/|title=About The Show|archivedate=29 December 2014}}</ref> He was also a regular presenter for ''The Open'' on the [[Sky Poker]] channel.\n\nIn 2016 he toured with ''[[The Rocky Horror Show]]''<ref>{{cite news|url=http://stv.tv/news/features/1347822-five-minute-interview-norman-pace-on-the-two-rons-and-rocky-horror-show/|title=Five-minute interview: Norman Pace on the Two Rons and Rocky Horror Show|website=STV News|author=Pamela Tulloch|date=28 March 2016}}</ref> and in 2017 the new production of ''[[Hairspray (musical)|Hairspray]]'', playing the role of Wilbur Turnblad.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wintergardensblackpool.co.uk/uncategorized/hairspray-the-musical-star-cast-announcement/|title=Hairspray the Musical Star Cast Announcement|website=Winter Gardens Blackpool|date=5 June 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170809191349/http://www.wintergardensblackpool.co.uk/uncategorized/hairspray-the-musical-star-cast-announcement/|archivedate=9 August 2017}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|name=Norman Pace|id=0655154}}\n* [http://pokerdb.thehendonmob.com/player.php?a=r&n=28024 Norman Pace Hendon Mob poker tournament results]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pace, Norman}}\n[[Category:1953 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Greenwich]]\n[[Category:English male comedians]]\n[[Category:English male television actors]]\n[[Category:Poker commentators]]\n[[Category:People from Newark-on-Trent]]\n[[Category:People educated at Magnus Church of England School]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Nottinghamshire]]\n[[Category:People from Dudley]]\n[[Category:Male actors from the West Midlands (county)]]\n[[Category:English male stage actors]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toWest Midlands(link changed toWest Midlands (region)) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Norman_Pace"}
